{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488698","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488698"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:52:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:52:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"509"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/509"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.84,0.14,0.01,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"509"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50016"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/509"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"509"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35269"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"430"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2643"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2807"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40669"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50016","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50016"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to a rural emergency department with a six hour history of severe pain in his left eye. In addition to visual blurring, he is nauseated. He had four similar episodes over the last five months and on each occasion there was spontaneous resolution of symptoms after about an hour. His visual acuity is 6/60 in the left eye and 6/6 in the right. The intraocular pressure is 48mmHg in the left eye and 22mmHg in the right eye. The conjunctival vessels in the left eye are severely injected and the cornea is hazy and injected. The anterior chamber is shallow with cells and flare. The pupil is vertically mid-dilated and does not react to direct or consensual light. He is given an anti-emetic.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In addition to intravenous acetazolamide, which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical timolol and review in 24-hours","Topical timolol and transfer for ophthalmological assessment","Transfer for ophthalmological assessment","Topical antibiotic and review in 24-hours","Outpatient ophthalmological referral"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has acute angle closure glaucoma. This is an ophthalmological emergency. As the patient is in a rural emergency department, the most appropriate management option involves giving \u003Cstrong\u003Etopical timolol and transfer for ophthalmological assessment.\u003C/strong\u003E It is already stated that the patient will be given intravenous acetazolamide. Topical timolol is a beta-blocker which reduces intraocular pressure. A \u003Cstrong\u003Ereview in 24-hours or outpatient ophthalmological referral\u003C/strong\u003E in not appropriate - this patient needs urgent ophthalmological assessment as untreated high intraocular pressures can cause irreversible optic nerve damage. Although \u003Cstrong\u003Etransfer for ophthalmological referral\u003C/strong\u003E is required, some initial management can be instituted at the rural ED prior to transfer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute angle closure glaucoma is an emergency and requires urgent treatment and ophthalmological referral."],"references":["Bowling, B. (2015). Kanski\u2019s clinical ophthalmology (8th ed.). W B Saunders."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":